KNN : K Nearest Neighbours

KNN Intuition : You are the average of 5 people you spend the most time with.

Suppose we have a dataset : IQ | CGPA | Placement and based on IQ and GPA we predict whether the candidate is placed or not 

We decide a value of k , means we consider 3 nearset neighbours.

We get a query point , we know his iq and gpa , now predict whether hes placed or not.


In knn , for the given query point , we take the euclidean distance from all points to the query point.
100 distacnes caluclated , one for each point and sort them in ascending order. And thr closet points will be on the top .
We apply a rule called majority count. 
Then we decide the class label of neareat point. 

While training the model make sure all data is on same scale , like some cols might be in percentages and some in decimals and some in whole numbers and some in floats , make sure all are aligned with only 1 unit of measurement
If we dont use same scale , the distance will be calculated inaccurately as one metric will dominate on one side. 
KNN can be worked in any dimensional data


How to select K? Depends on data , 2 ways: 
1) Heuristic approach : sqrt(n) , n- no of observations , aviod even value for k , cause we take k=4 and our query point lies around 2 points for class 0 and lies around 2 points for class 1 then we get conflict.
2) Experimentation : cross validation : consider 1000 obs , 800 in train aqnd 200 in test , create diff knn models with k=1,2,3,4.... , then we train these knns on the train data and then use use the test data on the models and then find the accuracy scores.
                    and select that model whos accuracy score is highest.

